# Security Playbook

Apply these rules in all code and when adding backend/APIs.

## Authentication & Sessions (01–03)
- **01** JWT session expiry ≤ 7 days; use refresh token rotation.
- **02** Never use AI-built auth. Use Clerk, Supabase, or Auth0.
- **03** API keys strictly in env (e.g. `process.env`, Flutter: `--dart-define` / env files); never in chat or repo.

## Secure API Development (04–08)
- **04** Rotate secrets at least every 90 days.
- **05** Verify all suggested packages for security before adding (e.g. `dart pub outdated`, check CVEs).
- **06** Prefer newer, more secure package versions.
- **07** After dependency changes run audit (e.g. `npm audit fix` or Dart equivalent).
- **08** Sanitize all inputs; use parameterized queries only.

## API & Access Control (09–13)
- **09** Enable Row-Level Security in DB from day one.
- **10** No `console.log`/`print` in production; Flutter: use `debugPrint` only in lib (disabled in release).
- **11** CORS restricted to allow-listed production domain.
- **12** Validate redirect URLs against an allow-list.
- **13** Auth and rate limiting on every endpoint.

## Data & Infrastructure (14–18)
- **14** Cap AI API costs in code and dashboard.
- **15** DDoS protection (e.g. Cloudflare, Vercel edge).
- **16** Storage: users access only their own files.
- **17** Validate uploads by signature, not by extension.
- **18** Verify webhook signatures before processing payment data.

## Other (19–24)
- **19** Permissions enforced server-side; UI checks are not security.
- **20** Log critical actions: deletions, role changes, payments, exports.
- **21** Implement real account deletion flows.
- **22** Automate backups and test restores.
- **23** Keep test and production fully separate.
- **24** Never let webhooks touch real systems in test.
